
	stdv: a simple yet usable implementation of a vector<T> in and for C

	~ ABOUT:
	stdv, is a implementation for having a vector library for C programming language.
	It attempts to implement most of the std::vector capabilities from C++ (see https://cppreference.com/cpp/container/vector).

	~ API INTERFACE
	Access
	* `stdv_at`       method: returns the element at position `at`
	* `stdv_front`    method: access the first element 
	* `stdv_back`     method: access the last element 
	* `stdv_data`     method: returns a pointer to the underlying array serving as element storage
	* `stdv_pbeg`     method: returns a pointer to the first element of the array
	* `stdv_pend`     method: returns a pointer to the last element of the array
	* `stdv_pat`      method: returns a pointer to the specified position `at`
	Capacity
	* `stdv_empty`    method: checks whether the container is empty 
	* `stdv_size`     method: returns the number of elements
	* `stdv_capacity` method: returns the current vector capacity
	* `stdv_is_mut`   method: returns wether the vector is mutable or not
	* `stdv_reserve`  method: reserves storage
	* `stdv_shrink`   method: reduces memory usage by freeing unused memory 
	* `stdv_clear`    method: clears the contents
	Modifiers
	* `stdv_put`      method: inserts an element at the end of the array and returns it (1)
	* `stdv_pop`      method: deletes the last element of the array and returns it
	* `stdv_insert`   method: inserts the element at the position given
	* `stdv_erase`    method: erase the element at position given
	* `stdv_imut`     method: shrinks the array and makes the array imutable

	~ INDEXING ERRORS:
	stdv will behave as normal arrays act, if the index provided is greater than the current array's
	length, stdv will perform the operation anyways. Hope for the best and take care of indexing

